quotes.text: "This is a return to Soviet times when in order to send a paper to an international journal, we had to get a permission specifying that the result is not new and important and hence may be published abroad,"
quotes.speaker: Mikhail Gelfand

quotes.text: "Be reminded that current legislation obliges scientists to get approval prior to publication of any article and conference talk or poster,"
quotes.speaker: Vladimir Putin

quotes.text: "despite the obvious absurdity of the whole situation"
quotes.speaker: Shuper

quotes.text: "Many scientists in Russia don't dare to speak openly,"
quotes.speaker: Shuper

quotes.text: "But I know that many are very unhappy about the degradation of their academic freedom."
quotes.speaker: Shuper

quotes.text: "The problem is that it appears that all scientific output is being treated as potentially classified,"
quotes.speaker: Fyodor Kondrashov

quotes.text: "This creates an unhealthy research climate with some scientists preferring not to share information — not to give a talk at a conference abroad, for example. I fear that the authorities will choose to apply this law selectively against their critics."
quotes.speaker: Sergey Salikhov

quotes.text: "Basically, anything new and potentially useful can now be interpreted to be a state secret,"
quotes.speaker: Konstantin Severinov

quotes.text: "A sad sign of overall deterioration here is that many are sheepishly following any absurdity instilled by the bureaucrats,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "I am going to ignore it and hope that a sufficient number of colleagues would do the same."
quotes.speaker: Unknown
